\int_{0}^x \frac{dt}{\sin^2 t +\cos t} =\int_{0}^x \frac{dt}{-\cos^2 t +\cos t+1}  =-\int_{0}^x \frac{dt}{\cos^2 t -\cos t-1} 
X=\cos t
X^2-X-1=0 \Leftrightarrow X=\frac{1-\sqrt{5}}{2} \mbox{and } X=\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}
\frac{1}{X^2-X-1}=\frac{\frac{\sqrt{5}}{5}}{X-(\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2})}-\frac{\frac{\sqrt{5}}{5}}{X-(\frac{1-\sqrt{5}}{2})}
-\int_{0}^x \frac{dt}{\cos^2 t -\cos t-1}= -\int_{0}^x \frac{\frac{\sqrt{5}}{5}}{\cos t-(\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2})}dt + \int_{0}^x \frac{\frac{\sqrt{5}}{5}}{\cos t-(\frac{1-\sqrt{5}}{2})}dt
\tan(t/2)
y = \tan(t/2)
dy = \sec^2(t/2) \dfrac{dt}2 \implies dt = \dfrac{2 dy}{1+y^2}
\sin(t) = \dfrac{2y}{1+y^2} \,\,\,\text{ and }\,\,\, \cos(t) = \dfrac{1-y^2}{1+y^2}
I = \int \dfrac{dt}{\sin^2(t) + \cos(t)} = \int \dfrac{2dy}{\dfrac{4y^2}{1+y^2} + 1-y^2} = \int \dfrac{2(1+y^2) dy}{1+4y^2 - y^4}
